time, what compelled him to flee to a far less powerful one? Albert Braz’s Apostate Englishman: Grey Owl the Writer and the Myths is the first comprehensive study of Grey Owl’s cultural and political image in light of his own writings. While the denunciations of Grey Owl after his death are often interpreted as a rejection of his appropriation of another culture, Braz argues that what troubled many people was not only that Grey Owl deceived them about his identity, but also that he had forsaken European culture for the North American Indigenous way of life. That is, he committed cultural apostasy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aConservationistszCanadavBiography. 0aCulture in literature. 0aIndians in literature. 0aIndigenous peoples in literature. 0aNatural history literaturezCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aNature writerszCanadavBiography. 0aPassing (Identity) in literature. 0aPolitics in literature. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Literary.2bisacsh  aAnahareo.  aArchie Belaney.  aGrey Owl.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311127402708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015z978311127703540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978088755504640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780887555046423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780887555046/original  a978-3-11-127402-7  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  a978-3-11-127703-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles